natural problem: The diagonals of rectangle $PQRS$ intersect at point $X$.  If $PS = 10$ and $RS=24$, then what is $\cos \angle PXS$?
natural solution: [asy] pair P,Q,R,SS,X,F; SS = (0,0); P = (0,5); R = (12,0); Q= R+P; X = Q/2; F = foot(SS,P,R); draw(F--SS--R--Q--P--SS--Q); draw(P--R); label("$P$",P,NW); label("$Q$",Q,NE); label("$R$",R,SE); label("$S$",SS,SW);
To find $\cos \angle PXS$, we build a right triangle with $\angle PXS$ as one of its acute angles.
We do so by drawing altitude $\overline{SF}$ from $S$ to diagonal $\overline{PR}$ as shown.
We then have $\cos \angle PXS = \cos\angle FXS = \frac{FX}{XS}$. The Pythagorean Theorem gives us $PR = QS = 26$, so $XP=SX = QS/2 = 13$.

We also have $\triangle FPS \sim \triangle SPR$ by AA Similarity (both are right triangles and $\angle SPR = \angle FPS$), so \[\frac{FP}{PS} = \frac{SP}{PR}.\]This gives us \[FP = PS \cdot \frac{SP}{PR} = \frac{10\cdot 10}{26} = \frac{50}{13}.\]Finally, we have $FX = XP - FP = 13 - \frac{50}{13} = \frac{119}{13}$, so \[\cos \angle PXS = \frac{FX}{XS} = \frac{119/13}{13} = \boxed{\frac{119}{169}}.\]
